New multisample textures feature seems not working with DX11.
I change the RenderToTexture example
- renderTexture->SetSize(1024, 768, Graphics::GetRGBFormat(), TEXTURE_RENDERTARGET);
+ renderTexture->SetSize(1024, 768, Graphics::GetRGBFormat(), TEXTURE_RENDERTARGET, 8);
As result the renderTexture becomes one-colored.

The same changes work fine with DX9.

Hello, i have switched from PBRDeferred to PBRDeferredHWDepth (can you confirm me that this is better in terms of performances ?)

I have made a custom height fog shader that was working well with linear depth but since i have switched to hardware depth i have some troubles and the height fog is **working only under certain camera angles**.
I have already adapted the shader to use the "ReconstructDepth" function.

This method for reconstructing the world pos was working well with linear depth: const float3 worldPos = iFarRay \* depth; 

Or maybe it is a problem with screenpos ? 

Here is the VS and PS shader. 

Can you help me there ? Thanks

```
void VS(float4 iPos : POSITION,
    out float2 oScreenPos : TEXCOORD0,
    out float3 oFarRay : TEXCOORD1,
    out float4 oPos : OUTPOSITION)
{
    float4x3 modelMatrix = iModelMatrix;
    float3 worldPos = GetWorldPos(modelMatrix);
    oPos = GetClipPos(worldPos);
    oScreenPos = GetScreenPosPreDiv(oPos);
    oFarRay = GetFarRay(oPos);  
}

#ifdef COMPILEPS

void PS(float2 iScreenPos : TEXCOORD0,
    float3 iFarRay : TEXCOORD1,
    out float4 oColor : OUTCOLOR0)
{
    const float fogDist = 16000.0 * cHeightFog_Power;

    const float4 color = Sample2D(DiffMap, iScreenPos);

    float depth = Sample2D(DepthBuffer, iScreenPos).r;
    depth = ReconstructDepth(depth);

    const float3 worldPos = iFarRay * depth;

    const float depth2 = 1.0 - clamp(length(worldPos)/fogDist, 0.0, 0.25); // 1.0 
    const float height = (worldPos.y + cHeightFog_CameraElevation)*0.01;

    const float fogFactor =  clamp(exp(-height*depth2+1.0) * (1.0-exp(depth2*2-2)),0.0,1.0);
    const float diffFactor = 1-fogFactor;

    const float3 dirRay = normalize(iFarRay);

    const float layer = clamp(exp(((1-dirRay.y)-1) * (0.5 + cHeightFog_CameraElevation*0.001)),0,1);

    //const float3 fogcolor = 1.0 * cHeightFog_Color.rgb * layer;
    const float3 fogcolor = (cHeightFog_Color.rgb * layer) * clamp(abs(-1.0 + depth), 0.8, 1.0);

    oColor = color * diffFactor + float4(fogcolor.r, fogcolor.g, fogcolor.b, 0.0) * fogFactor;
}

#endif
```

This error happens during accesses to arrays of some script objects.
The code looks innocent (I don't do anything majical).
I just add objects to arrays then parse these arrays, and
after some iterations this happens. The code is quite complex to use as example,
but I could not make minimal example.

So basic construction which fails is this (code part):

```
class DataListItem {
     float left, top, right, bottom;
...
}

class DataList {
    Array<DataListItem> queue;
    void add(DataListItem d)
    {
        queue.Push(d);
    }
   DataListItem  fetch()
   {
        DataListItem item = queue[0];
        queue.Erase(0);
        return item;
   }
...

    void process_queue()
    {
        while(!queue.empty) {
            DataListItem item = fetch();
            /* grow function splits rectangles in item
            and returns array of them */
            Array<DataListItem> res = grow(item);
            if (res.empty) {
               ...
            } else {
               for (int i; i < res.length; i++)
                   add(res[i]);
        }
    }
}
...
```

